{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d7c40b34-1b88-442b-8723-7c040b7a6d23","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it watches for file changes and re-runs tests automatically:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter` flag scopes it to just your failing test for faster feedback.\n\n**About the bug:** `RemoveStock` doesn't validate quantity — it just subtracts without throwing. You'll need to add a guard in `RemoveStock`, e.g.:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply that fix?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a3c24ea9-1453-4a2e-9c53-d334957c6315","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for the test project. Since this is using .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as specified in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me check what's available. The `dotnet watch` command can be used with test projects. Let me suggest the right approach.\n\nFor .NET test projects, the way to get hot reload is `dotnet watch test`. This will watch for file changes and re-run tests automatically.\n\nBut wait - with the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner (as configured in global.json), there might also be `dotnet test --hotreload` available in .NET 10. \n\nI'll go with `dotnet watch test` as the standard approach since it's well-established and reliable. I can also mention the option to filter to specific failing tests if needed.","outputTokens":449,"requestId":"1BC7:1AB7E8:23064E3:26CDC4D:6A03DA55"},"id":"6e776f3c-de3b-497e-91c9-be51d3b7506b","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:56:50.408Z","parentId":"2a4c1c3a-445b-436c-8016-f329bc941700"}
